{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"936a86e1-c24b-4ff7-9761-8a9b4a945eb9","content":"The working directory is empty, so I'll answer from general .NET/macOS knowledge.\n\nOn macOS, when `createdump` isn't available (common with NativeAOT since it's not bundled), you can recover a crash dump using the **macOS built-in core dump mechanism**:\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** before running your app:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS stores them in `/cores/` by default):\n   ```bash\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n\n3. **Run your app** — when it crashes, macOS writes a `core.<pid>` file to `/cores/`.\n\n4. **If no core file appears**, check that:\n   - SIP (System Integrity Protection) isn't blocking it.\n   - The `/cores/` directory exists and is writable:\n     ```bash\n     sudo mkdir -p /cores && sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n     ```\n\n5. **Analyze the dump** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n6. **Alternatively**, check **Console.app → Crash Reports** (`~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`) for a `.ips` crash log with stack traces — useful even without a full core dump.\n\n**Key difference from CoreCLR apps**: NativeAOT doesn't ship `createdump`, so you rely entirely on the OS-level core dump facility rather than the managed `createdump` tool.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fa9087c6-c985-4f5c-bce2-302ea8f6254b","outputTokens":371,"requestId":"A042:24D482:999B7A:BC0A37:6A013703"},"id":"f1396a8a-7429-498f-b5fc-2ac74c087c8d","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:55:25.190Z","parentId":"0cc359c4-5a56-47ee-b05f-f99f737bfd16"}
